{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5b614e9d-8d1b-436e-ba1c-9fc6f3b131d2","content":"This is a TUnit project using Microsoft Testing Platform (MTP) natively (`OutputType: Exe`). Use the `--filter-class` flag:\n\n```bash\ndotnet run -- --filter-class *SmsNotificationTests\n```\n\nThe `--` separates `dotnet run` arguments from arguments passed to the test executable. The `*` wildcard matches the full namespace prefix (`Contoso.Notifications.Tests.SmsNotificationTests`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ac84e6c4-62a4-4daa-8585-7bc76cc36b68","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is a TUnit project. TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) natively. To filter by class name in TUnit/MTP, you use the `--filter-class` option or the `--filter` option with a VSTest filter expression.\n\nSince TUnit is built on MTP, the filtering syntax depends on whether they're using VSTest compatibility or native MTP.\n\nLooking at the csproj, there's no `<TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>` or similar. TUnit 0.6.x uses MTP natively.\n\n\nSince the project outputs as an executable, I'd run it with `dotnet run` and pass the filter arguments after `--`, so something like `dotnet run -- --filter-class *SmsNotificationTests` should work. The `dotnet test` command might also work depending on whether VSTest compatibility is configured, but with native MTP, the executable approach is more direct.","outputTokens":512},"id":"052dc605-9c41-49d6-a065-a4f3607d6a38","timestamp":"2026-04-05T01:32:01.935Z","parentId":"89994689-e2de-4dc4-8814-ca5853b3cd76"}
